Package com.fudan.sw.dsa.project2.bean

Class Graph

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.fudan.sw.dsa.project2.bean.Graph
  • public class Graph
extends java.lang.Object
    The entrance of the shortest path searching algorithm and it stores the vertices in the graph. It contains the graph initialization method that creates new vertices and edges storing specified data, the get path methods that correspond to the demands in the project and a number of utility functions that makes code reuse more widespread.
    Author:
    Wang, Chen

      • getTime

        private static int getTime​(@NotNull

        It parses the input string format time into the readable time and then calculates the difference of the two times. Note that the start time should be earlier than the end time and the formats are according to the xls file the TA distributes

      • addVertex

        public Vertex addVertex​(Vertex preStation,
                        java.lang.String stationName,
                        java.lang.String lineName,
                        java.lang.String time1,
                        java.lang.String time2,
                        double latitude,
                        double longitude)
        This method is called when initializing the graph, it adds the station as a vertex into the graph. It modifies the existing vertex if the station already exists or new a vertex if it is the first time that such a vertex is read. While newing the vertex objects, this method also maintains the previous station of the new station, the edge that connects the two edges, and the GPS info of the new address. Note that the station name of the transfer stations on different lines is the same.
        Parameters:
        preStation - The previous station of the current station along the edge
        stationName - The name of the station
        lineName - The name of the line connecting the station that is being added
        time1 - The arriving time of the subway at the previous station
        time2 - The arriving time of the subway at the current station
        latitude - Latitude of the current subway station
        longitude - Longitude of the current subway station
        Returns:
        The just newed vertex

public @Nullable Vertex getStation​(java.lang.String address)

      • nearestStation

        private Vertex nearestStation​(Address address)
        Search for the nearest station with the requesting address It calculates the straight line distance of the address and the subway station and iterates through the entire station list. Note that the address has no restriction
        Parameters:

        Returns:
        The nearest station from the address

      • getPath

        private java.util.ArrayList<Vertex> getPath​(Vertex startV,
                                            Vertex endV)
        The core entrance of the algorithm, it calls the dijkstra algorithm and gets a shortest weight path from the two subway stations. Note that the two vertices must be the stations that have already been in the station array list and This method does not call the dijkstra algorithm if the two requested vertices are the same.
        Parameters:
        startV - The source of the graph
        endV - The sink of the graph
        Returns:
        The path returned from the dijkstra algorithm

      • getPathAndTime

        private java.util.ArrayList<Vertex> getPathAndTime​(Vertex vertexS,
                                                   Vertex vertexE,
                                                   Address start,
                                                   Address end)
        The auxiliary method for the last two method for conveniently get the path and total consuming time for any requested station and the specified start and end address. Note that the global variable time is refreshed and updated in this method
        Parameters:
        vertexS - Start subway station
        vertexE - End subway station
        start - The start address
        end - The end address
        Returns:
        The same as get path method
